===Etymology===
Thought to be the same word as {{och-l|丈}} "gentleman, older man, husband", i.e. "someone who walks with, or leans on, a staff"; though unlikely.

According to {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}}, this is an areal word. Compare {{cog|lus|tiang||staff, stick, crutch}}, {{cog|mkh-okm|toŋ||shaft, stock, shank}}, {{m|mkh-okm|-toṅa||stock, stem, stick}}, and {{cog|km|ដង||pole, shaft, handle, yoke, body, trunk}}. {{zh-ref|Benedict (1976)}} also compares this to {{cog|tai-pro|*de:ŋ ~ *tʰe:ŋ||stick, bar}}, {{cog|ms|tiang||pillar, post, pole}}, {{cog|fj|ndia||stick, handle}}, and to reconstructed {{w|Austro-Tai languages|Proto-Austro-Tai}} *''(n)ti(j)aŋ''.

A derivative, attested in {{w|Zuozhuan}}, is the verb {{och-l|杖|tr=draŋh}} "to lean on", with suffix *''-s'' → *''-h'' → {{zh-l|去聲}}.

